03776nam a22005295i 9780520908765DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t19891989cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209087657 a10.1525/97805209087652doi  a(DE-B1597)520497  a(OCoLC)317459489  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aSD225.T67 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a338.174909521 aTotman, Conrad, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Green Archipelago :bForestry in Pre-Industrial Japan /cConrad Totman. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1989] 4cÂ©1989  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tA Brief Chronology -- tMaps -- tIntroduction: An Overview of Preindustrial Japanese Forest History -- tPart One. A Millennium of Exploitation Forestry -- tPart Two. The Emergence of Regenerative Forestry in Early Modern Japan -- tConclusion -- tBibliographical Essay: Scholarship on Preindustrial Japanese Forestry, 1880-1980 -- tNotes -- tGlossaries -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvery foreign traveler in Japan is delighted by the verdant forest-shrouded mountains that thrust skyward from one end of the island chain to the other. The Japanese themselves are conscious of the lush green of their homeland, which they sometimes refer to as "the green archipelago." Yet, based on its fragile geography and centuries of extremely dense human occupation, Japan today should be an impoverished, slum-ridden, peasant society subsisting on a barren, eroded moonscape characterized by bald mountains and debris-strewn lowlands.In fact, as Conrad Totman argues in this pathbreaking work based on prodigious research, this lush verdue is not a monument to nature's benevolence and Japanese aesthetic sensibilities, but the hard-earned result of generations of human toil that have converted the archipelago into one great forest preserve. Indeed, the author shows that until the late 1600s Japan was well on her way to ecological disaster due to exploitative forestry. During the Tokugawa period, however, an extraordinary change took place resulting in a system of "regenerative forestry" that averted the devastation of Japan's forests. The Green Archipelago is the only major Western-language work on this subject and a landmark not only in Japanese history, but in the history of the environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aForest policyxJapan. 0aForest policyzJapan. 0aForests and forestryxJapan. 0aForests and forestryzJapan. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press eBook Package Archivez978311063534840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520908765423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520908765.jpg  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles